00:10:13.430 --> 00:10:15.690
into this research project.

00:10:15.690 --> 00:10:18.880
About a year after I
completed my Ph.D. dissertation

00:10:18.880 --> 00:10:21.970
on Italian Renaissance music
theory, I just happened

00:10:21.970 --> 00:10:23.480
to be minding my own business

00:10:23.480 --> 00:10:26.340
at the Youngstown
Jewish Community Center.

00:10:26.340 --> 00:10:28.930
When the executive director of
the center approached me to see

00:10:28.930 --> 00:10:32.710
if I was interested in taking
home the JCC's collection

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:35.880
of dusty 78 RPM records.

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:38.130
He was just looking for a
chump who could help them clean

00:10:38.130 --> 00:10:40.040
out some closet space.

00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:43.410
But I'm kind of a sucker for
free records and free CDs

00:10:43.410 --> 00:10:44.850
and other media like that.

00:10:44.850 --> 00:10:46.190
So I took the bait.

00:10:46.190 --> 00:10:49.380
The collection contains
many sacred recordings

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:51.200
by star cantors.

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:52.650
Novelty songs.

00:10:52.650 --> 00:10:54.240
Comedy skits.

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:56.580
There're even some records
that have Yiddish songs

00:10:56.580 --> 00:11:01.740
and Latin dance craze
tunes on the other side.

00:11:01.740 --> 00:11:04.770
So what I did was I started
looking at the records and ended

00:11:04.770 --> 00:11:06.660
up making a little
database of them.

00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:09.490
And I thought this is
interesting, but, you know,

00:11:09.490 --> 00:11:10.960
what would happen if I
looked at more records?

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:14.440
And I ended up creating a
database of about 6,000 records,

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:18.570
which I did from
using online catalogs

00:11:18.570 --> 00:11:21.540
and printed discographies.

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:23.230
And basically getting
information,

00:11:23.230 --> 00:11:25.870
reputable information from
wherever I could find it.

00:11:25.870 --> 00:11:28.300
I also spent some
time at the YIVO,

00:11:28.300 --> 00:11:31.000
which is the Yiddish
Institute in New York City.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.160
And also at, residency at
the Judaica Sound Archives

00:11:34.160 --> 00:11:36.320
in Florida Atlantic University.

00:11:36.320 --> 00:11:39.190
In that initial collection
the disc

00:11:39.190 --> 00:11:41.930
that interested me
most was a recording

00:11:41.930 --> 00:11:46.370
of a descriptive overture
called the "Kishineff Pogrom."

00:11:46.370 --> 00:11:48.650
And I had two questions
for this record.

00:11:48.650 --> 00:11:52.230
First of all, why would
Jews want to listen to it?

00:11:52.230 --> 00:11:54.180
And, you know, why would
anyone want to listen

00:11:54.180 --> 00:11:56.890
to a musical depiction
of a recent atrocity?

00:11:56.890 --> 00:11:58.480
What's the point?

00:11:58.480 --> 00:12:01.460
Wasn't living it enough?

00:12:01.460 --> 00:12:03.310
So that was my first question.

00:12:03.310 --> 00:12:05.950
And the second question was,
you know, what are the sounds

00:12:05.950 --> 00:12:07.970
on these records
supposed to represent?

00:12:07.970 --> 00:12:09.330
If this describes a pogrom,

00:12:09.330 --> 00:12:13.070
how do I connect the
notes to what a pogrom is?

00:12:13.070 --> 00:12:16.260
So investigating these things,

00:12:16.260 --> 00:12:18.410
I found that there's actually
a fascinating history here.

00:12:18.410 --> 00:12:21.370
And I put it all
together with mostly

00:12:21.370 --> 00:12:24.590
by studying sheet music
that's in the Irene Heskes

00:12:24.590 --> 00:12:27.090
and other collections in
the Library of Congress.

00:12:27.090 --> 00:12:28.630
So another reason
why I'm very glad

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:29.940
to present this research here.

00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:34.840
In case you're not familiar with
the Kishineff Pogrom, Kishineff

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:38.600
or Chisinau is the
current capital of Moldova.

00:12:38.600 --> 00:12:41.260
And at the time of
the pogrom in 1904,

00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:44.570
Jews made up about 30
percent of the population.

00:12:44.570 --> 00:12:48.090
In the years leading up to
the pogrom, the "Bessarabetz,"

00:12:48.090 --> 00:12:49.800
a local newspaper edited

00:12:49.800 --> 00:12:53.240
by the rabid anti-Semite
Pavolaki Krushevan,

00:12:53.240 --> 00:12:56.480
printed a number of articles
against the Jewish community.

00:12:56.480 --> 00:12:59.180
In 1903 he found
the perfect catalyst

00:12:59.180 --> 00:13:01.860
to set off the violence
that was to come.

00:13:01.860 --> 00:13:04.650
Two Christian children had
been found dead in the area

00:13:04.650 --> 00:13:07.050
around Kishineff and
Krushevan claimed

00:13:07.050 --> 00:13:10.050
that Jews had murdered the
children and drained their blood

00:13:10.050 --> 00:13:11.610
to make matzo for Passover.

00:13:11.610 --> 00:13:15.680
And this is a classic kind
of lie told about Jews

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:18.740
when people need to justify
violence against them.

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:21.450
And in case you're not
familiar with Jewish practice,

00:13:21.450 --> 00:13:23.340
Jews have never used
blood to cook.

00:13:23.340 --> 00:13:27.190
It's not kosher, so it's just
not something we would do.

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:30.050
Nevertheless, on Easter
Sunday of that year,

00:13:30.050 --> 00:13:33.470
mobs headed into the
Jewish areas of the city.

00:13:33.470 --> 00:13:35.840
And they murdered many
people, and then they raped

00:13:35.840 --> 00:13:38.330
and pillaged for several days.

00:13:38.330 --> 00:13:40.740
It was this atrocity
that inspired the music

00:13:40.740 --> 00:13:43.150
that I'm now going to discuss.

00:13:45.810 --> 00:13:50.240
The Kishineff Pogrom of 1903 is
one of many events memorialized

00:13:50.240 --> 00:13:52.950
in Judaism's tragic past.

00:13:52.950 --> 00:13:55.130
Although the number of
casualties does not compare

00:13:55.130 --> 00:13:58.460
with the Holocaust or
even many other pogroms,

00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:01.850
the massacre had a great
influence on Jewish activism,

00:14:01.850 --> 00:14:05.120
even for those who will
already immigrated to America.

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:08.380
Indeed, in a 2013
lecture on Kishineff

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:11.190
at the YIVO Institution
for Jewish Research,

00:14:11.190 --> 00:14:14.480
historian Steven Zipperstein
claimed that the fallout

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:18.100
of the pogrom inspired
Jewish-American involvement

00:14:18.100 --> 00:14:22.840
in not only the creation
of the NAACP and the ACLU,

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:26.070
but also the election of
President Barack Obama.

00:14:26.070 --> 00:14:30.220
Furthermore, Zipperstein argues
that the extraordinary response

00:14:30.220 --> 00:14:33.070
to Kishineff, which
played heavily in American

00:14:33.070 --> 00:14:35.310
and Yiddish-American newspapers,

00:14:35.310 --> 00:14:38.150
was fuelled by an
important Zionist leader

00:14:38.150 --> 00:14:41.240
who coincidentally
resided in Kishineff.

00:14:41.240 --> 00:14:45.400
Indeed, Yakov Bernstein-Kogan
directed a Zionist post office

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:47.260
out of Kishineff, which he used

00:14:47.260 --> 00:14:50.540
to communicate activities
throughout Russia and beyond.

00:14:50.540 --> 00:14:53.370
In the immediate
aftermath of the pogrom,

00:14:53.370 --> 00:14:56.700
he energized his network of
international connections

00:14:56.700 --> 00:14:59.890
to disseminate information
about the violence.

00:14:59.890 --> 00:15:01.810
Descriptions and
eyewitness accounts

00:15:01.810 --> 00:15:05.080
in the press were accompanied
by benefit concerts.

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:06.860
Poetry. Books.

00:15:06.860 --> 00:15:08.520
And new music.

00:15:08.520 --> 00:15:10.190
The speed at which new artifacts

00:15:10.190 --> 00:15:12.810
about the pogrom
appeared is remarkable.

00:15:12.810 --> 00:15:16.820
In fact, the "New York Times
Tribune" reported in 1903

00:15:16.820 --> 00:15:19.930
that one Yiddish theater
staged a dramatic reenactment

00:15:19.930 --> 00:15:24.220
of the massacre within 48
hours after it occurred.

00:15:24.220 --> 00:15:26.380
Producers of the
reenactment did not strive

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:29.060
for a literal presentation
of the events.

00:15:29.060 --> 00:15:32.440
Instead, basing the action
on previous atrocities.

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:34.880
Their underlying messages
about the need for Jews

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:38.180
to find a homeland, however,
were already familiar

00:15:38.180 --> 00:15:39.960
and superceded specific details.

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:45.600
I want to briefly show some of
the newspapers from which I've,

00:15:45.600 --> 00:15:48.460
getting all this information
about all the press releases.

00:15:48.460 --> 00:15:51.400
And these are documents
that you can, anyone can go

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:54.120
to the Library of
Congress website.

00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:56.850
And you can actually search
for individual words like

00:15:56.850 --> 00:15:58.150
"Kishineff," and it will bring

00:15:58.150 --> 00:16:00.030
up where Kishineff
occurs in any paper.

00:16:00.030 --> 00:16:01.950
So it's just an amazing tool,

00:16:01.950 --> 00:16:03.250
and you can learn
so much from this.

00:16:03.250 --> 00:16:06.780
Here's a page from the "New
York Daily Tribune," 1903.

00:16:06.780 --> 00:16:10.320
And we can see the
top of this column,

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:12.740
a letter from Kishineff
about the events.

00:16:12.740 --> 00:16:17.390
Later down here is an article
about the Russian ambassador

00:16:17.390 --> 00:16:20.750
to America who's complaining
that the news is all exaggerated

00:16:20.750 --> 00:16:23.650
and it didn't really happen.

00:16:23.650 --> 00:16:26.430
Here's another page from
the "St. Louis Republic."

00:16:26.430 --> 00:16:30.340
And we see there's an
article about a father,

00:16:30.340 --> 00:16:33.100
a family in St. Louis
whose father escaped

00:16:33.100 --> 00:16:35.460
and how they're trying
to bring the family

00:16:35.460 --> 00:16:37.500
to America from Kishineff.

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:40.280
There's an article about
Israel Zangwill's statements

00:16:40.280 --> 00:16:41.580
about the pogrom.

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:43.240
Zangwill was a very
famous playwright

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:44.640
who coined the term
"melting pot."

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:46.990
So he's an important
figure in American letters.

00:16:46.990 --> 00:16:49.470
There's just, there's no
end to what you can get

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:50.790
from just doing, you know,

00:16:50.790 --> 00:16:54.240
basic archival work
in these newspapers.

00:16:56.360 --> 00:16:58.590
Much of the media
coverage strove

00:16:58.590 --> 00:17:01.780
to promote a Zionist
agenda as well

00:17:01.780 --> 00:17:03.820
as raise funds for the victims.

00:17:03.820 --> 00:17:06.930
For example, an article in
the "Brooklyn Daily Eagle,"

00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:09.550
seen here, begins
with the question,

00:17:09.550 --> 00:17:11.720
What is the lesson of Kishineff?

00:17:11.720 --> 00:17:15.720
And responds, Ringing around
the world, loud and clear,

00:17:15.720 --> 00:17:19.650
voiced by the great leaders
of Zion comes the answer.

00:17:19.650 --> 00:17:21.330
Return to Palestine.

00:17:21.330 --> 00:17:22.630
Rebuild the temple.

00:17:22.630 --> 00:17:24.870
Resurrect the nation.

00:17:24.870 --> 00:17:27.580
Furthermore, new
books on anti-Semitism

00:17:27.580 --> 00:17:31.620
in Russia also urged a
solution to the Jewish problem.

00:17:31.620 --> 00:17:35.550
The Irish activist and statesman
Michael Davitt visited Russia

00:17:35.550 --> 00:17:36.970
immediately after the pogrom.

00:17:36.970 --> 00:17:38.420
And wrote articles about it

00:17:38.420 --> 00:17:41.280
for William Randolph
Hearst's newspapers.

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:42.950
His reporting served
as the basis

00:17:42.950 --> 00:17:44.880
for the book "Within the Pale."

00:17:44.880 --> 00:17:48.160
The true story of anti-Semitic
persecution in Russia,

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:51.080
which he published
later in 1903.

00:17:51.080 --> 00:17:54.700
Although Davitt claimed to be in
line with the spirit and program

00:17:54.700 --> 00:17:59.300
of anti-Semitism, in some cases
he argues that he wrote the book

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:02.970
to put forward a plea for the
objects of the Zionist movement.

00:18:09.600 --> 00:18:12.460
In addition to book-length
discussions and reactions

00:18:12.460 --> 00:18:16.170
in the newspapers, gruesome
poems like Shimen Frug's

00:18:16.170 --> 00:18:20.070
"Hot Rachmunes" or "Have
Mercy" were disseminated widely

00:18:20.070 --> 00:18:22.500
to inspire sympathy
in fellow Jews

00:18:22.500 --> 00:18:25.110
and raise funds for survivors.

00:18:25.110 --> 00:18:28.230
There were also musical works
published in the aftermath.

00:18:28.230 --> 00:18:30.510
And the Library of
Congress' collection includes

00:18:30.510 --> 00:18:31.810
many examples.

00:18:31.810 --> 00:18:35.670
I have just a couple here of
many that you can look at online

00:18:35.670 --> 00:18:37.580
or I guess see in the library.

00:18:37.580 --> 00:18:41.260
The first, "Hot Rachmunes,"
is a setting of the poem.

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:44.680
Someone took Shimen Frug's
poem and set it as a song.

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:47.810
The second, "The farewell
of the Jews to Kishineff,"

00:18:47.810 --> 00:18:50.590
is a descriptive piece
like the work I'm going

00:18:50.590 --> 00:18:53.690
to speak in detail about.

00:18:53.690 --> 00:18:57.720
And also written as a response
to the pogrom and ways of,

00:18:57.720 --> 00:19:01.880
get people involved with the
issues of Jews in Europe.

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:03.180
So there are many
other examples.

00:19:03.180 --> 00:19:05.580
I just chose a couple.

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:11.080
Shimen Frug's poem also
inspired Herman Shapiro's 1904

00:19:11.080 --> 00:19:15.370
"Kishineff Massacre," a
descriptive work for solo piano.

00:19:15.370 --> 00:19:18.660
Featuring a series of
short musical tableau,

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:21.900
Shapiro designed his composition
to bring the severity

00:19:21.900 --> 00:19:25.220
of the pogrom into the living
rooms of American Jews.

00:19:25.220 --> 00:19:28.370
And we can assume
to move their hearts

00:19:28.370 --> 00:19:30.790
to joining the Zionist cause.

00:19:30.790 --> 00:19:33.500
Shapiro's affective
score, with its ties

00:19:33.500 --> 00:19:37.230
to Western European musical
traditions and foregrounding

00:19:37.230 --> 00:19:41.680
of what we might call
stereotypically Jewish elements,

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:44.390
stands out as a useful
point of departure

00:19:44.390 --> 00:19:48.450
to discuss how composers
marketed Jewish catastrophe.

00:19:48.450 --> 00:19:50.940
Educated listeners and
performers on the plight

00:19:50.940 --> 00:19:52.240
of their brethren in Europe.

00:19:52.240 --> 00:19:55.140
And pressed for Zionist action.

00:19:55.140 --> 00:19:59.030
Shapiro's massacre can also help
us decode other musical media

00:19:59.030 --> 00:20:02.600
about Kishineff whose
aesthetic logic is not as clear.

00:20:02.600 --> 00:20:05.960
Such as the record which
I will discuss later.

00:20:07.290 --> 00:20:10.770
Herman Shapiro appears to
have been quite successful

00:20:10.770 --> 00:20:13.690
in marketing tragedy
to Jewish audiences.

00:20:13.690 --> 00:20:15.540
The printed preface
to the score of his

00:20:15.540 --> 00:20:18.460
"Dr. Herzl Elegy"
includes a testimonial

00:20:18.460 --> 00:20:20.990
from a concert he gave in 1899.

00:20:20.990 --> 00:20:23.830
And it reads, "There
was given recently

00:20:23.830 --> 00:20:26.680
in Louisville a genuine
Hebrew concert.

00:20:26.680 --> 00:20:29.470
The program was distinctly
Jewish in character.

00:20:29.470 --> 00:20:31.570
The whole tragedy of
Israel found utterance

00:20:31.570 --> 00:20:33.330
in the eloquence of the music.

00:20:33.330 --> 00:20:35.700
Every feast of gladness
and every day of sorrow

00:20:35.700 --> 00:20:38.580
and oppression had
its record in melody."

00:20:38.580 --> 00:20:42.770
The same review claims that
everybody present who heard the

00:20:42.770 --> 00:20:46.830
"plaintive cry of his
own people" responded

00:20:46.830 --> 00:20:49.200
sympathetically to the music.

00:20:49.200 --> 00:20:52.580
It seems that Shapiro and his
live performances received the

00:20:52.580 --> 00:20:55.560
same reaction from audiences
that he hoped would occur

00:20:55.560 --> 00:20:57.970
in the living rooms
and salons of the Jews

00:20:57.970 --> 00:21:01.390
who would purchase his
"Kishineff Massacre."

00:21:01.390 --> 00:21:05.770
The printed score, published
by Asna Goldberg in 1904,

00:21:05.770 --> 00:21:08.160
is a striking as the
music it contains.

00:21:08.160 --> 00:21:11.670
The bright red cover, attention
grabbing in its own right,

00:21:11.670 --> 00:21:14.670
frames a ghastly
illustration of the pogrom.

00:21:14.670 --> 00:21:17.830
In the foreground angry
Russians whip an elderly man

00:21:17.830 --> 00:21:21.660
and strangle a young woman while
a naked toddler inexplicably

00:21:21.660 --> 00:21:23.370
flies through the air.

00:21:23.370 --> 00:21:26.290
A silhouetted mob in
smoke fill the background,

00:21:26.290 --> 00:21:29.370
which is outlined by a
whip and a bloody sword.

00:21:29.370 --> 00:21:32.900
The macabre image is more than
suitable to attract Jews looking

00:21:32.900 --> 00:21:35.910
to contemplate or
memorialize suffering.

00:21:35.910 --> 00:21:38.930
And the Yiddish titles betray
the marketing intentions

00:21:38.930 --> 00:21:42.220
of the publisher.

00:21:42.220 --> 00:21:45.700
Inside the cover we
find a Yiddish text

00:21:45.700 --> 00:21:47.410
in the English translation

00:21:47.410 --> 00:21:50.460
of Shimen Frug's
poem "Hot Rachmunes."

00:21:50.460 --> 00:21:53.910
It's inclusion in the score
and connections to the music,

00:21:53.910 --> 00:21:57.420
which I will discuss below,
help us understand the function

00:21:57.420 --> 00:21:59.400
of Shapiro's piece as a tool

00:21:59.400 --> 00:22:02.760
for domestic entertainment
and edification.

00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:06.500
The Kishineff pogrom
may be a novel subject

00:22:06.500 --> 00:22:09.160
for a solo piano work,
but the structure

00:22:09.160 --> 00:22:12.380
of Shapiro's composition
follows the formula common

00:22:12.380 --> 00:22:14.590
to instrumental battle pieces.

00:22:14.590 --> 00:22:16.300
Which were popular
in America during

00:22:16.300 --> 00:22:17.810
and just after the Civil War.

00:22:17.810 --> 00:22:20.490
A full history of
musical depictions

00:22:20.490 --> 00:22:22.940
of battles would take
us back centuries

00:22:22.940 --> 00:22:26.000
in the Western European
canon and include clever

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.650
and entertaining works
by Clement Janequin.

00:22:28.650 --> 00:22:29.950
William Byrd.

00:22:29.950 --> 00:22:31.250
Heinrich Biber.

00:22:31.250 --> 00:22:33.880
And even Beethoven's much
criticized battle symphony

00:22:33.880 --> 00:22:36.170
titled "Wellington's Victory."

00:22:36.170 --> 00:22:38.740
According to Richard Crawford
in "America's Musical Life,"

00:22:38.740 --> 00:22:43.030
however, most American composers
modeled their battle pieces

00:22:43.030 --> 00:22:46.710
on the Bohemian Frantisek
Kocvara's "Battle of Prague,"

00:22:46.710 --> 00:22:49.950
which was first published
in the 1780s.

00:22:49.950 --> 00:22:53.110
Kocvara's setting depicts
Frederick the Great's victory

00:22:53.110 --> 00:22:55.990
over the Austrians during
the Seven Years' War

00:22:55.990 --> 00:22:58.770
through a series of
short musical episodes.

00:22:58.770 --> 00:23:01.570
He writes in common
western musical topics

00:23:01.570 --> 00:23:04.520
such as march rhythms,
horn calls and Sturm

00:23:04.520 --> 00:23:08.150
and Drang passages to
represent the preparations for

00:23:08.150 --> 00:23:10.250
and execution of warfare.

00:23:10.250 --> 00:23:13.770
The music was first
published in the U.S. in 1793.

00:23:13.770 --> 00:23:17.650
And inspired many new solo piano
works based on American battles

00:23:17.650 --> 00:23:20.650
from the Revolutionary
and Civil wars as well

00:23:20.650 --> 00:23:24.660
as the Spanish-American
War a century later.

00:23:24.660 --> 00:23:28.190
Musicologist Elizabeth Morgan
has recently published research

00:23:28.190 --> 00:23:30.280
on Civil War battle pieces.

00:23:30.280 --> 00:23:32.470
And her conclusions about
these works are helpful

00:23:32.470 --> 00:23:35.760
in understanding Shapiro's
music for Kishineff.

00:23:35.760 --> 00:23:38.940
First of all, Civil War
battle pieces were composed

00:23:38.940 --> 00:23:41.100
for domestic performances.

00:23:41.100 --> 00:23:44.300
Especially by amateur
female pianists.

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.040
The importance of acquiring
piano skills for young women

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:49.860
at the turn of the 20th
century is well-documented

00:23:49.860 --> 00:23:52.420
in home journals,
music periodicals

00:23:52.420 --> 00:23:54.290
and other literature
of the time.

00:23:54.290 --> 00:23:59.280
In one 1892 book-length guide
for housewives titled "Queen

00:23:59.280 --> 00:24:02.740
of the Home," Emma Churchman
Hewitt considers piano playing

00:24:02.740 --> 00:24:04.990
as a key component
of home making.

00:24:04.990 --> 00:24:08.860
But lamented conditions in
which "Daughters were expected

00:24:08.860 --> 00:24:11.830
to make night hideous
and their lives a burden

00:24:11.830 --> 00:24:15.420
by their weary hours
of practice."

00:24:15.420 --> 00:24:18.150
Even Jewish women, many of
them being first generation

00:24:18.150 --> 00:24:21.820
immigrants, sought to prove
their talents on the piano.

00:24:21.820 --> 00:24:25.010
Joseph Rumshinsky, one of the
most prolific Jewish composers

00:24:25.010 --> 00:24:27.070
and arrangers of
the Yiddish theater,

00:24:27.070 --> 00:24:29.570
published many didactic
musical works.

00:24:29.570 --> 00:24:32.240
And describes his
clientele in his memoir

00:24:32.240 --> 00:24:34.460
"Klangen fun mayn lebn."

00:24:34.460 --> 00:24:37.600
He writes, "From 10:00
in the morning until 3:00

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:40.200
in the afternoon, I taught
young women recently married

00:24:40.200 --> 00:24:43.090
who wanted to show their
husbands they could play piano.

00:24:43.090 --> 00:24:45.730
From 3:00 until 7:00 I
taught schoolchildren.

00:24:45.730 --> 00:24:48.170
And then from until 10:00
or 11:00 in the evening,

00:24:48.170 --> 00:24:52.610
I taught shop girls and office
girls who wanted to get married.

00:24:52.610 --> 00:24:55.840
Rumshinsky's students may have
been looking for a husband,

00:24:55.840 --> 00:24:58.500
but their skills would have
also served as a conduit

00:24:58.500 --> 00:25:01.260
for the edifying messages
contained in works

00:25:01.260 --> 00:25:03.510
like Shapiro's "Kishineff
Massacre."

00:25:03.510 --> 00:25:06.860
The battle pieces served
as an entertaining vehicle

00:25:06.860 --> 00:25:11.040
for families to celebrate their
side's military achievements.

00:25:11.040 --> 00:25:14.670
Long before Facebook
news feeds and Twitter,

00:25:14.670 --> 00:25:18.090
battle pieces also supplemented
journalistic reports.

00:25:18.090 --> 00:25:21.390
Providing intricate details of
the fighting with a descriptive

00:25:21.390 --> 00:25:23.490
and stirring musical
accompaniment.

00:25:23.490 --> 00:25:27.240
Not surprisingly, Northern
publishes printed works based

00:25:27.240 --> 00:25:28.670
on Union victories.

00:25:28.670 --> 00:25:29.970
And the triumphs

00:25:29.970 --> 00:25:32.700
of the Confederacy were
covered by Southern presses.

00:25:32.700 --> 00:25:35.720
Shapiro's massacre seems
counterintuitive in this regard

00:25:35.720 --> 00:25:39.880
as the pogrom was certainly not
a victory for Jews to celebrate.

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:43.070
On the other hand, the battle
genre offered appropriate means

00:25:43.070 --> 00:25:46.500
for transplanted families
to relate to the instability

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:49.360
of Jewish life in Europe
while strengthening the piano

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:54.790
technique of young women eager
to enter respectable society.

00:25:54.790 --> 00:25:57.230
Shapiro could have modeled
the composition on reports

00:25:57.230 --> 00:26:00.190
of the pogrom posted
in U.S. papers.

00:26:00.190 --> 00:26:02.920
As early as May 1903,
the "New York Times"

00:26:02.920 --> 00:26:06.610
and "The Sun" published
unsettling eyewitness accounts

00:26:06.610 --> 00:26:08.010
of the violence.

00:26:08.010 --> 00:26:12.380
But Shapiro's descriptive music
mostly ignores specific details

00:26:12.380 --> 00:26:16.740
in favor of stock musical topics
commonly found in battle pieces.

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:20.970
For example, many battle pieces
include a morning bugle call

00:26:20.970 --> 00:26:22.400
or reveille.

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:24.850
And this is the one from
Kocvara's "Battle of Prague."

00:26:24.850 --> 00:26:27.140
And it's, you know,
it's trumpet music.

00:26:27.140 --> 00:26:28.940
This one goes.

00:26:28.940 --> 00:26:35.380
[ Music Sounds ]

00:26:35.380 --> 00:26:37.230
And so forth.

00:26:37.230 --> 00:26:39.920
This is one from the
Battle of Gettysburg.

00:26:39.920 --> 00:26:46.930
And, again, very much what
we think of as trumpet music.

00:26:46.930 --> 00:26:48.230
[ Music Sounds ]

00:26:48.230 --> 00:26:49.530
And so forth.

00:26:49.530 --> 00:26:50.830
Although the published accounts

00:26:50.830 --> 00:26:53.890
of the pogrom do not
feature a bugle call,

00:26:53.890 --> 00:26:56.510
Shapiro includes the
bugle call of the rioters.

00:26:56.510 --> 00:27:09.130
[ Piano Music ]

00:27:09.130 --> 00:27:10.740
Another obligatory section

00:27:10.740 --> 00:27:13.110
of battle pieces is
a musical depiction

00:27:13.110 --> 00:27:15.640
of the violent acts
of war itself.

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:18.940
Attack music has a long history
in western classical music.

00:27:18.940 --> 00:27:21.040
For one prominent example,

00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:24.380
the Italian composer
Claudio Monteverdi suggested

00:27:24.380 --> 00:27:28.020
in the 1638 preface of his
eighth book of madrigals

00:27:28.020 --> 00:27:31.000
that an agitated or violent
affect could be rendered

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:34.970
in music through a succession
of quick repeated notes.

00:27:34.970 --> 00:27:37.150
He put his theory into
use in the dramatic

00:27:37.150 --> 00:27:40.360
"Combattimento di Tancredi
e Clorinda" or "Combat

00:27:40.360 --> 00:27:42.140
between Tancredi and Clorinda."

00:27:42.140 --> 00:27:46.630
In this short excerpt the
narrator describes a deadly duel

00:27:46.630 --> 00:27:48.510
between the title characters.

00:27:48.510 --> 00:28:17.040
[ Music ]

00:28:17.040 --> 00:28:19.300
Monteverdi's so-called
agitated style caught

00:28:19.300 --> 00:28:20.600
on throughout Europe.

00:28:20.600 --> 00:28:23.220
And could be heard in countless
pieces that describe battles,

00:28:23.220 --> 00:28:25.430
storms and violent behavior.

00:28:25.430 --> 00:28:27.040
In the late 18th century,

00:28:27.040 --> 00:28:30.440
composers for the piano often
used dexterous passage work

00:28:30.440 --> 00:28:33.450
at a quick tempo to
represent military action.

00:28:33.450 --> 00:28:37.180
And here's the attack music from
Kocvara's "Battle of Prague."

00:28:37.180 --> 00:28:40.600
And you can see the
quick Alberti Bass figure

00:28:40.600 --> 00:28:41.900
in the piano.

00:28:41.900 --> 00:28:44.830
And then these melodic figures,
two of them that I have circled,

00:28:44.830 --> 00:28:48.050
I'll come back to in a second.

00:28:48.050 --> 00:28:51.470
Shapiro's attack music, what
he labels as the hellish work

00:28:51.470 --> 00:28:54.000
in full force, fits
this paradigm.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:55.990
And the principal motive
is clearly borrowed

00:28:55.990 --> 00:28:57.440
from the "Battle of Prague."

00:28:57.440 --> 00:28:58.740
So you see the same figure.

00:28:58.740 --> 00:29:01.730
It goes kind of like
[music sounds].

00:29:01.730 --> 00:29:07.210
And it's the same as the figure
in Kocvara's attack music.

00:29:07.210 --> 00:29:11.030
Elizabeth Morgan notes that
in Civil War battle pieces the

00:29:11.030 --> 00:29:13.810
attack music always
stays in a major key.

00:29:13.810 --> 00:29:16.290
Shapiro, in contrast
to this tradition,

00:29:16.290 --> 00:29:19.330
tried to represent an
attack on Jews in his music

00:29:19.330 --> 00:29:20.690
and adds chromatic tones

00:29:20.690 --> 00:29:23.510
to create Jewish
sounding harmonies.

00:29:23.510 --> 00:29:26.110
At first the mode
merely shifts to G minor.

00:29:26.110 --> 00:29:28.480
But later on scaler
runs in arpeggios

00:29:28.480 --> 00:29:31.000
with augmented seconds
bring the ethnic nature

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:32.910
of the conflict into focus.

00:29:32.910 --> 00:29:34.710
So now let's hear both examples.

00:29:34.710 --> 00:29:57.050
[ Piano Music ]

00:29:57.050 --> 00:29:59.510
Shapiro.

00:29:59.510 --> 00:30:29.290
[ Piano Music ]

00:30:29.290 --> 00:30:31.580
Although the "Kishineff
Massacre" certainly borrows

00:30:31.580 --> 00:30:33.540
from the battle music tradition,

00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:37.080
it notably does not
contain actual battle music.

00:30:37.080 --> 00:30:39.700
Instead Shapiro focuses
on the victims,

00:30:39.700 --> 00:30:43.410
directing the listener towards
the work's didactic function.

00:30:43.410 --> 00:30:47.610
Many battle pieces include
a brief lamentation section

00:30:47.610 --> 00:30:50.700
to represent fallen troops
on either side of the fight.

00:30:50.700 --> 00:30:55.250
So here's one from the
"Battle of Waterloo" from 1910.

00:30:55.250 --> 00:30:59.380
And you can see it's, the
title "Lamentation," adagio.

00:30:59.380 --> 00:31:00.680
So it's slow.

00:31:00.680 --> 00:31:02.200
Con expressione or
with expression.

00:31:02.200 --> 00:31:05.790
It's a very lyrical and
subdued piece of music.

00:31:05.790 --> 00:31:08.590
This is a very interesting
one from Charles Grobe's

00:31:08.590 --> 00:31:09.890
"The Battle of Fort Donelson."

00:31:09.890 --> 00:31:14.270
And in this case the
music is very choral-like.

00:31:14.270 --> 00:31:17.910
Like something a four-part
choir might sing in church.

00:31:17.910 --> 00:31:20.500
The music is actually
"My Country Tis of Thee."

00:31:20.500 --> 00:31:24.860
And the text is the names
of the Northern soldiers

00:31:24.860 --> 00:31:26.420
who had died in the battle.

00:31:26.420 --> 00:31:28.210
And you can see them
all listed there.

00:31:28.210 --> 00:31:30.620
So if you were performing
this piece at home

00:31:30.620 --> 00:31:33.230
and someone was narrating the
work, they would actually read

00:31:33.230 --> 00:31:36.450
through all the names, you
know, possibly people you know

00:31:36.450 --> 00:31:37.750
who died in the battle.

00:31:37.750 --> 00:31:44.210
So it's a very affective
way of lamenting the fallen.

00:31:44.210 --> 00:31:46.320
In the "Kishineff
Massacre," however,

00:31:46.320 --> 00:31:49.700
Shapiro composes more
lamentation than action,

00:31:49.700 --> 00:31:53.650
reserving three of the work's
seven sections for this purpose.

00:31:53.650 --> 00:31:56.030
Unlike the other parts
of the composition,

00:31:56.030 --> 00:31:59.450
these excerpts predominantly
feature stereotypically

00:31:59.450 --> 00:32:00.750
Jewish music.

00:32:00.750 --> 00:32:02.050
Slow tempi.

00:32:02.050 --> 00:32:04.950
Inflections of the
so-called Ahava Rabbah scale

00:32:04.950 --> 00:32:08.070
and cantorial gestures
and ornaments.

00:32:08.070 --> 00:32:11.490
The first example, labeled
"The victims in their Agony,"

00:32:11.490 --> 00:32:13.580
is a brief depiction of anguish.

00:32:13.580 --> 00:32:17.510
Three chords played in tremolo
followed by a plaintive cadenza.

00:32:17.510 --> 00:32:46.590
[ Piano Music ]

00:32:46.590 --> 00:32:49.740
For the descriptive labels
of the two other examples,

00:32:49.740 --> 00:32:53.280
Shapiro draws directly from
the text of Frug's poem.

00:32:53.280 --> 00:32:55.940
Emphasizing the connection
between this piece

00:32:55.940 --> 00:32:58.360
of musical entertainment
and the campaign

00:32:58.360 --> 00:33:00.300
that inspired the poetry.

00:33:00.300 --> 00:33:02.620
Of special note is
the third lamentation

00:33:02.620 --> 00:33:04.200
"The Living Cry for Bread."

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:07.980
Which eludes to the refrain that
ends each stanza of the poem.

00:33:07.980 --> 00:33:11.340
And serves as the finale
of the entire composition.

00:33:11.340 --> 00:33:15.130
The refrain reads, "Brethren
sisters, mercy, mercy,

00:33:15.130 --> 00:33:17.250
grave and awful is the woe.

00:33:17.250 --> 00:33:22.370
Hasten shrouds to wrap the dead,
hasten give the living bread."

00:33:22.370 --> 00:33:24.960
"The Living Cry For Bread"
is easily the longest section

00:33:24.960 --> 00:33:26.620
in Shapiro's massacre.

00:33:26.620 --> 00:33:30.170
Its stately tempo, mournful
character and repetition

00:33:30.170 --> 00:33:33.710
of motives heard in the first
two lamentation sections help

00:33:33.710 --> 00:33:37.220
create a suitable
anti-finale for the work.

00:33:37.220 --> 00:33:39.730
In a recent article on
descriptive piano works,

00:33:39.730 --> 00:33:43.000
Jonathan Bellman notes how
Kocvara's "Battle of Prague"

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:46.620
and many other descriptive
works end with a familiar song.

00:33:46.620 --> 00:33:48.550
"The Living Cry For Bread"
is certainly the most

00:33:48.550 --> 00:33:50.110
song-like section.

00:33:50.110 --> 00:33:52.050
And even if it is
original music,

00:33:52.050 --> 00:33:54.740
its characteristic
melodic motives are similar

00:33:54.740 --> 00:33:56.120
to other plaintive Jewish tunes.

00:33:56.120 --> 00:33:57.920
Here is the opening.

00:33:57.920 --> 00:34:28.160
[ Piano Music ]

00:34:28.160 --> 00:34:31.270
Shapiro's publisher must
have noted the potential for

00:34:31.270 --> 00:34:33.860
"The Living Cry For Bread"
to be heard as a paradigm

00:34:33.860 --> 00:34:35.530
of tragic Jewish music.

00:34:35.530 --> 00:34:39.100
For they included an excerpt of
this section as an advertisement

00:34:39.100 --> 00:34:41.370
for Shapiro's work
in the sheet music

00:34:41.370 --> 00:34:45.370
for Joseph Rumshinsky's 1906
arrangement of the Yiddish song

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:48.660
"Eli, Eli," a classic of
Jewish pathos throughout the

00:34:48.660 --> 00:34:49.960
20th century.

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:51.890
And here's the edition
also from the Library

00:34:51.890 --> 00:34:53.190
of Congress collection.

00:34:53.190 --> 00:34:54.610
And you can see the cover.

00:34:54.610 --> 00:34:55.910
And then when you'd
open the cover,

00:34:55.910 --> 00:34:58.350
the first thing you would see
would be this page of music

00:34:58.350 --> 00:35:03.350
from Shapiro's work as a
kind of advertisement for it.

00:35:03.350 --> 00:35:05.510
Here's what that
tune sounds like.

00:35:05.510 --> 00:35:43.040
[ Music ]

00:35:43.040 --> 00:35:46.690
You can hear, very
similar in character.

00:35:46.690 --> 00:35:50.320
In short, Shapiro's
"Kishineff Massacre" follows

00:35:50.320 --> 00:35:52.890
in the tradition of battle
music for solo piano.

00:35:52.890 --> 00:35:56.620
But alters it significantly
by directing its performers'

00:35:56.620 --> 00:35:59.770
and listeners' attention
towards the tragic losers

00:35:59.770 --> 00:36:03.450
of the battle using stock,
stereotypical gestures

00:36:03.450 --> 00:36:06.080
to generate sympathy
for the Jewish cause.

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:09.290
It is likely that well-to-do
Jewish families in America

00:36:09.290 --> 00:36:10.590
who would have already
been familiar

00:36:10.590 --> 00:36:13.550
with the battle genre could
easily understand its new

00:36:13.550 --> 00:36:18.450
context and be moved to act on
its charitable exhortations.

00:36:18.450 --> 00:36:20.030
While Shapiro's musical
depiction

00:36:20.030 --> 00:36:24.250
of the Kishineff pogrom does not
convey the Zionist sentiments

00:36:24.250 --> 00:36:27.130
common to the American
press reports, another work

00:36:27.130 --> 00:36:31.340
by the composer reveals how his
tragic Jewish battle piece might

00:36:31.340 --> 00:36:34.190
be aligned with the
Zionist cause.

00:36:35.210 --> 00:36:38.050
Shapiro would draw his audiences
further towards the Jewish

00:36:38.050 --> 00:36:40.630
poetics of domestic
music making with his

00:36:40.630 --> 00:36:43.410
"Dr. Herzl Elegy"
for solo piano.

00:36:43.410 --> 00:36:46.760
Which he published in July
1904, five months after his

00:36:46.760 --> 00:36:48.970
"Kishineff Massacre"
and just one month

00:36:48.970 --> 00:36:51.480
after the death of
Theodore Herzl.

00:36:51.480 --> 00:36:53.470
That Shapiro would
musically honor the life

00:36:53.470 --> 00:36:55.360
of the Zionist leader
on the heels

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:57.180
of his Kishineff piece suggests

00:36:57.180 --> 00:37:00.010
that his earlier composition
should not stand apart

00:37:00.010 --> 00:37:03.910
from the Zionist enthusiasm
that followed the tragedy.

00:37:03.910 --> 00:37:08.170
The opening in Dante in G Ahava
Rabbah shares the same tonal

00:37:08.170 --> 00:37:12.250
center, G, tempo and character
of "The Living Cry For Bread"

00:37:12.250 --> 00:37:14.180
from the "Kishineff Massacre."

00:37:14.180 --> 00:37:15.690
Hinting that the
newer work begins

00:37:15.690 --> 00:37:17.510
with a previous piece left off.

00:37:17.510 --> 00:38:20.470
[ Piano Music ]

00:38:20.470 --> 00:38:23.720
All of the remaining sections,
which Shapiro introduces

00:38:23.720 --> 00:38:27.630
with either Yiddish odes to
Herzl by George Selikowitz

00:38:27.630 --> 00:38:31.400
or descriptive titles, feature
the same musical elements used

00:38:31.400 --> 00:38:34.810
to signify Jewishness in
the "Kishineff Massacre."

00:38:34.810 --> 00:38:36.530
Furthermore, connections

00:38:36.530 --> 00:38:39.940
to European musical topics
are far less apparent

00:38:39.940 --> 00:38:41.240
than in the previous work.

00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:44.970
In the elegy, the listener is
not invited to hear Jewish music

00:38:44.970 --> 00:38:47.380
in opposition to western idioms.

00:38:47.380 --> 00:38:51.100
To the contrary, as German
musicologist Jascha Nemtosov

00:38:51.100 --> 00:38:54.180
notes in his book "Zionism
in Music," Shapiro turns

00:38:54.180 --> 00:38:57.500
to Klezmer, incorporating
authentic sounding tunes

00:38:57.500 --> 00:39:00.770
in accompaniment patterns that
mimic the hammered dulcimer.

00:39:00.770 --> 00:39:03.690
For example, let's hear
the opening of the section

00:39:03.690 --> 00:39:05.790
"Hofnung's Tenor
von Zion's Harf"

00:39:05.790 --> 00:39:07.590
or "Hope's Hand on Zion's Harp."

00:39:07.590 --> 00:39:35.370
[ Piano Music ]

00:39:35.370 --> 00:39:38.480
Shapiro subtitled the
elegy "Funeral meditations

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:41.910
on the death of the Jewish
Siegfried, Zion's architect."

00:39:41.910 --> 00:39:44.950
A reference to the mythic
German hero and subject

00:39:44.950 --> 00:39:47.130
of Richard Wagner's
"Ring Cycle."

00:39:47.130 --> 00:39:50.640
It may be surprising that
Theodor Herzl was a huge fan

00:39:50.640 --> 00:39:53.070
of the anti-Semitic
composer Richard Wagner,

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:54.470
but it is quite true.

00:39:54.470 --> 00:39:57.130
And Shapiro may have
shared his enthusiasm.

00:39:57.130 --> 00:40:00.670
The three flat key signatures
seen throughout the elegy might

00:40:00.670 --> 00:40:03.040
be a reference to
Siegfried's funeral music

00:40:03.040 --> 00:40:05.040
in Act 3 of Gotterdammerung.

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:06.670
And the musical material
in one section

00:40:06.670 --> 00:40:10.430
of the elegy is reminiscent
of a Wagnerian leitmotif.

00:40:10.430 --> 00:40:12.460
Other parts of the
elegy, however,

00:40:12.460 --> 00:40:14.730
show little Wagnerian influence.

00:40:14.730 --> 00:40:17.740
In this composition, Jewish
folk styles account for much

00:40:17.740 --> 00:40:19.520
of the musical material.

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:22.760
Even in the final movement
labeled "In the Future,"

00:40:22.760 --> 00:40:25.690
which is marked allegramente
or cheerfully,

00:40:25.690 --> 00:40:29.510
one can imagine a Klezmer
tooting joyfully on a clarinet.

00:40:29.510 --> 00:40:54.060
[ Piano Music ]

00:40:54.060 --> 00:40:56.010
A comparison with
the sonic world

00:40:56.010 --> 00:40:58.900
of "the Kishineff Massacre,"
we might hear the elegy

00:40:58.900 --> 00:41:01.750
as a musical realization
of the Zionist dream.

00:41:01.750 --> 00:41:04.840
A space in which Jewish
culture dominates throughout.

00:41:04.840 --> 00:41:06.140
On the other hand,

00:41:06.140 --> 00:41:09.180
Herman Shapiro's most popular
printed work was a collection

00:41:09.180 --> 00:41:10.790
of Jewish wedding dances.

00:41:10.790 --> 00:41:12.110
And it is just as possible

00:41:12.110 --> 00:41:16.330
that to compose the Herzl elegy
quickly he chose Klezmer idioms

00:41:16.330 --> 00:41:17.880
because he was already
adept at it

00:41:17.880 --> 00:41:21.410
and could complete the elegy
ahead of his competition.

00:41:21.410 --> 00:41:24.270
So now let's turn to
the record I found

00:41:24.270 --> 00:41:26.650
in the Youngstown
JCC's collection.

00:41:26.650 --> 00:41:30.350
It is difficult to
assess the impact

00:41:30.350 --> 00:41:32.780
of Shapiro's work
for solo piano.

00:41:32.780 --> 00:41:34.970
And because they were
likely played in private,

00:41:34.970 --> 00:41:37.480
domestic settings,
it is also unlikely

00:41:37.480 --> 00:41:40.050
that we will find concert
programs or reviews

00:41:40.050 --> 00:41:42.140
that document performances.

00:41:42.140 --> 00:41:43.630
There is evidence, however,

00:41:43.630 --> 00:41:46.310
that Shapiro's "Kishineff
massacre" influenced later

00:41:46.310 --> 00:41:49.510
musical representations
of the pogrom.

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:54.070
In 1924, the Victor Talking
Machine Company released a

00:41:54.070 --> 00:41:56.720
recording by conductor
Nathaniel Shilkret

00:41:56.720 --> 00:41:59.160
and the international
Concert Orchestra

00:41:59.160 --> 00:42:02.240
of another descriptive
Kishineff massacre.

00:42:02.240 --> 00:42:06.130
The marketing classification,
Yiddish descriptive overture

00:42:06.130 --> 00:42:08.510
and Yiddish writing
on the disc certified

00:42:08.510 --> 00:42:12.120
that this recording was
marketed to Jewish audiences.

00:42:12.120 --> 00:42:14.790
Victor discographies
provides some basic details

00:42:14.790 --> 00:42:16.210
about the production.

00:42:16.210 --> 00:42:18.570
But no information
exists that might tell us

00:42:18.570 --> 00:42:21.610
for certain what this
descriptive overture is meant

00:42:21.610 --> 00:42:22.910
to describe.

00:42:22.910 --> 00:42:27.460
The 1924 recording of
"Kishineff Massacre" follows the

00:42:27.460 --> 00:42:30.560
conventions of the
earlier work for piano.

00:42:30.560 --> 00:42:34.600
For example, Shapiro's work
begins with a short intro,

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:38.040
"The First Signal of the Storm,"
which features foreboding,

00:42:38.040 --> 00:42:41.510
repeated octaves
punctuated with thick chords.

00:42:41.510 --> 00:43:12.210
[ Piano Music ]

00:43:12.210 --> 00:43:15.530
The opening on the record
includes a similar gesture.

00:43:15.530 --> 00:43:18.970
But this time the ominous pedal
point is played by trombones,

00:43:18.970 --> 00:43:20.530
the usual harbingers of death

00:43:20.530 --> 00:43:22.510
in Western European
classical music.

00:43:22.510 --> 00:43:45.380
[ Music ]

00:43:45.380 --> 00:43:48.290
The Jews are to be
represented by slow music,

00:43:48.290 --> 00:43:52.710
containing orientalist, excuse
me, orientalist inflections

00:43:52.710 --> 00:43:56.510
and rhapsodic cadenzas
played on violin or clarinet.

00:43:56.510 --> 00:44:37.810
[ Music ]

00:44:37.810 --> 00:44:39.780
The violence of the
event is represented

00:44:39.780 --> 00:44:42.140
by up tempo attack sections.

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:44.890
The first of which does not
show any stereotypical markers

00:44:44.890 --> 00:44:47.600
of Jewishness and
sounds like finale music

00:44:47.600 --> 00:44:49.510
for an operatic overture.

00:44:49.510 --> 00:45:18.790
[ Music ]

00:45:18.790 --> 00:45:22.700
The second up tempo
section, the works finale,

00:45:22.700 --> 00:45:24.900
sounds like an Eastern
European dance introduced

00:45:24.900 --> 00:45:26.440
by trumpet calls.

00:45:26.440 --> 00:45:29.260
Although the ethnic character
of the music is not distinct,

00:45:29.260 --> 00:45:32.480
it may reflect the reports
of a journalist who noted

00:45:32.480 --> 00:45:34.110
that in the immediate aftermath

00:45:34.110 --> 00:45:37.400
of the pogrom indifferent
citizens gathered each evening

00:45:37.400 --> 00:45:40.230
in the royal garden in
Kishineff to, quote,

00:45:40.230 --> 00:45:42.720
and this is Monte Pancower's
[assumed spelling] translation,

00:45:42.720 --> 00:45:45.230
"To enjoy the music
of the dragoon band,

00:45:45.230 --> 00:45:48.830
which performed Polish polkas
as well as Hungarian csardas

00:45:48.830 --> 00:45:52.510
and Russian marches
in faultless fashion."

00:45:52.510 --> 00:46:18.230
[ Music ]

00:46:18.230 --> 00:46:21.420
Without further documentation,
we have to use our imagination

00:46:21.420 --> 00:46:23.600
to determine the
intended image evoked

00:46:23.600 --> 00:46:26.470
by each section of the overture.

00:46:26.470 --> 00:46:28.790
The timing of the
recording is peculiar

00:46:28.790 --> 00:46:30.760
as it appears during
an era of uncertainty

00:46:30.760 --> 00:46:32.790
for Jews in the United States.

00:46:32.790 --> 00:46:35.620
According to Eric Goldstein
in "the price of whiteness,"

00:46:35.620 --> 00:46:37.820
white America had become
increasingly anxious

00:46:37.820 --> 00:46:41.180
in the 1920s about the
so-called Jewish problem.

00:46:41.180 --> 00:46:42.900
And debates over
the place of Jews

00:46:42.900 --> 00:46:45.090
in American society
carried forth

00:46:45.090 --> 00:46:49.060
in published articles,
symposia and exposes.

00:46:49.060 --> 00:46:52.040
Furthermore, although America
had been the number one

00:46:52.040 --> 00:46:54.830
destination for Jewish
immigrants leaving Europe,

00:46:54.830 --> 00:47:01.000
the Johnson-Reed Act of
1924 restricted their entry,

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:04.390
forcing many immigrants
to settle in Palestine.

00:47:04.390 --> 00:47:07.050
Given the unstable nature
of Jewish life in America

00:47:07.050 --> 00:47:10.840
at that time, it seems odd that
Victor would release a recording

00:47:10.840 --> 00:47:13.570
that would remind Jews of
recent atrocities committed

00:47:13.570 --> 00:47:15.450
by a host nation.

00:47:15.450 --> 00:47:16.750
On the other hand,

00:47:16.750 --> 00:47:19.400
record company executives
were not too concerned

00:47:19.400 --> 00:47:22.610
about the content of the
ethnic records they produced.

00:47:22.610 --> 00:47:24.760
From one example, L.L.C.
Book [assumed spelling],

00:47:24.760 --> 00:47:27.320
who was Columbia's
head of ethnic records,

00:47:27.320 --> 00:47:31.070
wrote in a 1920 issue of
"Talking Machine World" that

00:47:31.070 --> 00:47:33.750
"The foreigner is not particular

00:47:33.750 --> 00:47:35.750
in his selection
of foreign music.

00:47:35.750 --> 00:47:38.190
Simply he desires
music which reminds him

00:47:38.190 --> 00:47:40.320
of his old folks
and his old home.

00:47:40.320 --> 00:47:42.140
There's hardly any of
the foreign records

00:47:42.140 --> 00:47:43.840
which will not do this."

00:47:43.840 --> 00:47:48.200
The recording of the "Kishineff
Massacre" could certainly evoke

00:47:48.200 --> 00:47:52.790
memories of Russia, although
not necessarily pleasant ones.

00:47:52.790 --> 00:47:56.100
The Victor recording also
suggests how Jewish American

00:47:56.100 --> 00:47:57.400
engagement with the plight

00:47:57.400 --> 00:48:01.340
of European Jews may have
changed by the 1920s.

00:48:01.340 --> 00:48:05.080
In a 1906 essay, "The
Menace of Mechanical Music,"

00:48:05.080 --> 00:48:08.310
America's most famous band
leader and composer of the era,

00:48:08.310 --> 00:48:11.370
John Philip Sousa raged
against the fledging

00:48:11.370 --> 00:48:13.460
phonograph industry.

00:48:13.460 --> 00:48:16.320
Above all other complaints,
Sousa argued

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:17.620
that the proliferation

00:48:17.620 --> 00:48:20.260
of talking machines would
produce a terrible change

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:21.930
in America's musical culture.

00:48:21.930 --> 00:48:25.500
Noting "For when music
can be heard in the homes

00:48:25.500 --> 00:48:28.960
without the labor of study
and close application

00:48:28.960 --> 00:48:31.970
and without the slow process
of acquiring a technique,

00:48:31.970 --> 00:48:34.340
it will be simply
a question of time

00:48:34.340 --> 00:48:37.010
when the amateur
disappears entirely."

00:48:37.010 --> 00:48:41.900
Although Sousa scholar Pat
Warfield has demonstrated

00:48:41.900 --> 00:48:45.740
that Sousa was more interested
in revising copyright laws

00:48:45.740 --> 00:48:48.050
than protecting America's
musical heritage,

00:48:48.050 --> 00:48:50.730
Sousa's prophecy may be telling.

00:48:50.730 --> 00:48:54.600
In 1904, young Jewish women or
men may have practiced Shapiro's

00:48:54.600 --> 00:48:57.730
"Kishineff Massacre" for
hours, perfecting their skills

00:48:57.730 --> 00:49:00.500
of execution and interpretation.

00:49:00.500 --> 00:49:02.990
They would have performed the
piece at family gatherings,

00:49:02.990 --> 00:49:05.460
showing off their talents
while sharing the work's

00:49:05.460 --> 00:49:07.650
urgent message.

00:49:07.650 --> 00:49:08.950
Any one in the house

00:49:08.950 --> 00:49:11.010
or apartment during
practice sessions

00:49:11.010 --> 00:49:14.830
or performances may have seen
the sheet music, asked questions

00:49:14.830 --> 00:49:16.750
and learned about the situation.

00:49:16.750 --> 00:49:19.680
The 1924 recording,
on the other hand,

00:49:19.680 --> 00:49:22.580
would require much less
engagement from its audience.

00:49:22.580 --> 00:49:24.900
And serve more as a
memorial of the pogrom

00:49:24.900 --> 00:49:26.440
than a call to action.

00:49:26.440 --> 00:49:29.940
Now, I'd like to conclude
by discussing the placement

00:49:29.940 --> 00:49:33.640
of this recording in Victor's
catalog of ethnic records.

00:49:33.640 --> 00:49:37.620
The international concert
orchestra's discography covers a

00:49:37.620 --> 00:49:39.270
variety of ethnic styles.

00:49:39.270 --> 00:49:41.050
Which the label could
have easily marketed

00:49:41.050 --> 00:49:43.220
to various immigrant groups.

00:49:43.220 --> 00:49:45.540
Most of the choices
are nostalgic.

00:49:45.540 --> 00:49:47.650
There are waltzes
for the Viennese.

00:49:47.650 --> 00:49:49.920
Music by Edvard Grieg
for the Norwegians.

00:49:49.920 --> 00:49:51.750
And folk songs for the Russians.

00:49:51.750 --> 00:49:55.870
The only international concert
orchestra disc that was marketed

00:49:55.870 --> 00:50:00.030
to Jews and features what one
might call Jewish music is this

00:50:00.030 --> 00:50:02.080
"Kishineff Massacre."

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:03.380
The listing suggests that,

00:50:03.380 --> 00:50:06.500
whereas some immigrant groups
wanted to dance the night away

00:50:06.500 --> 00:50:09.340
or sing folk songs,
the Jewish community,

00:50:09.340 --> 00:50:11.490
20 years after Kishineff,

00:50:11.490 --> 00:50:13.600
preferred to contemplate
their suffering

00:50:13.600 --> 00:50:16.710
and fragile safety
among gentile nations.

00:50:16.710 --> 00:50:20.110
Perhaps Shapiro's "Kishineff
Massacre" helped establish a

00:50:20.110 --> 00:50:22.530
soundtrack for such a practice.

