not just Jewish imagination is
a pivot point in that regard?

01:00:13.750 --> 01:00:15.050
&gt;&gt; Randall Goldberg: Thanks.

01:00:15.050 --> 01:00:16.350
That's an interesting question.

01:00:16.350 --> 01:00:19.430
Yeah, Salamone Rossi is a
perfect example of a composer.

01:00:19.430 --> 01:00:21.530
Writes in Hebrew, but it
sounds like Palestrina.

01:00:21.530 --> 01:00:24.170
It's just gorgeous polyphony.

01:00:24.170 --> 01:00:26.050
When I look at this stuff,
I look through it more,

01:00:26.050 --> 01:00:29.430
not so much, I talked about
a lot of the background

01:00:29.430 --> 01:00:30.730
of this music and kind

01:00:30.730 --> 01:00:33.070
of Western European
classical traditions.

01:00:33.070 --> 01:00:37.390
This is more of like
mass-marketed popular music.

01:00:37.390 --> 01:00:40.330
And in America around the
turn of the 20th century,

01:00:40.330 --> 01:00:42.680
there's so much of this
going on in Tin Pan Alley

01:00:42.680 --> 01:00:44.040
and all the publishing houses.

01:00:44.040 --> 01:00:46.330
And they're working
very hard to appeal

01:00:46.330 --> 01:00:48.300
to distinct marketing niches.

01:00:48.300 --> 01:00:53.160
So using these, you know,
almost kind of stereotypes

01:00:53.160 --> 01:00:57.670
of what might sound Jewish
works really well to show

01:00:57.670 --> 01:00:59.710
that that is supposed
to be Jewish music.

01:00:59.710 --> 01:01:03.260
It's a little bit like how in
silent films or in cartoons

01:01:03.260 --> 01:01:06.330
or something, if in a cartoon
of a Jewish person comes

01:01:06.330 --> 01:01:07.890
on the screen, you have
to hear "Hava Nagila."

01:01:07.890 --> 01:01:11.740
It's like, you know, it's a
little bit cartoonish like that.

01:01:11.740 --> 01:01:14.550
And it's, yeah, there is
a lot of cantorial music

01:01:14.550 --> 01:01:15.850
that sounds like this.

01:01:15.850 --> 01:01:17.150
And, you know, certain types

01:01:17.150 --> 01:01:19.090
of Jewish worship music
that sound like this.

01:01:19.090 --> 01:01:23.600
But it's so much more I think
the composer as marketing

01:01:23.600 --> 01:01:26.210
to their audience
to me in a sense.

01:01:26.210 --> 01:01:30.650
There are all kinds of
debates at this time.

01:01:30.650 --> 01:01:33.000
One is by the writer,

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:35.990
Lazare Saminsky was a
Russian-Jewish composer.

01:01:35.990 --> 01:01:38.460
And he writes in his book
on "Music in the Ghetto

01:01:38.460 --> 01:01:42.420
and the Bible," saying
that all this kind of,

01:01:42.420 --> 01:01:45.290
I hate to use the term
"exotic inflection."

01:01:45.290 --> 01:01:47.220
But what musicians would
call augmented seconds.

01:01:47.220 --> 01:01:49.090
All these things are
actually corruptions

01:01:49.090 --> 01:01:50.760
of real Jewish music.

01:01:50.760 --> 01:01:53.030
That the real music of the Bible
wouldn't have had these things.

01:01:53.030 --> 01:01:56.380
It was just picked up by Jews
wandering through Central Asia.

01:01:56.380 --> 01:01:58.800
So there's always
kind of disputes.

01:01:58.800 --> 01:02:01.710
But in America I
think still, you know,

01:02:01.710 --> 01:02:04.140
if people want something to
sound Jewish, they play a tune

01:02:04.140 --> 01:02:06.000
and they have, you know, they
those intervals in there.

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:08.190
And people say, oh, that's
supposed to represent Jews.

01:02:08.190 --> 01:02:10.190
That's the way I'm kind of
looking at it in this paper.

01:02:10.190 --> 01:02:14.260
You know, if you look at later
in the 20th century into someone

01:02:14.260 --> 01:02:15.720
like Leonard Bernstein.

01:02:15.720 --> 01:02:17.470
Some, the things he
puts in his symphonies.

01:02:17.470 --> 01:02:21.680
When he's quoting the blessing
before reading a Haftarah

01:02:21.680 --> 01:02:22.980
in one of his symphonies.

01:02:22.980 --> 01:02:26.960
I mean, clearly he's trying to
create, you know, a Jewish sound

01:02:26.960 --> 01:02:29.060
that the Jews will
recognize as being Jewish.

01:02:29.060 --> 01:02:31.280
And it's similar to that.

01:02:31.280 --> 01:02:33.710
But it's hard for me to think

01:02:33.710 --> 01:02:35.950
of Herman Shapiro the same
way I might think of someone

01:02:35.950 --> 01:02:37.400
like Felix Mendelssohn.

01:02:37.400 --> 01:02:38.850
Because you know he's
someone who is really trying

01:02:38.850 --> 01:02:41.730
to show he's part of the
western classical tradition.

01:02:41.730 --> 01:02:45.040
Or Meyerbeer or some of
those other composers.

01:02:45.040 --> 01:02:46.990
He's writing music
to a mass market.

01:02:46.990 --> 01:02:51.150
He's not so much writing
music to please, you know,

01:02:51.150 --> 01:02:54.020
the "Neue Zeitschrift
fur Musik" in Germany.

01:02:54.020 --> 01:02:57.290
He's writing for his, you know,
for people to buy sheet music.

01:02:57.290 --> 01:03:00.460
I don't know if that
answers everything.

01:03:00.460 --> 01:03:10.220
&gt;&gt; You mentioned the of
speed of the communication

01:03:10.220 --> 01:03:14.730
and the publications in the
U.S. about the massacre.

01:03:14.730 --> 01:03:18.330
And I'm curious about the
back influence or knowledge

01:03:18.330 --> 01:03:25.270
or awareness of the music, this
composition or the reaction

01:03:25.270 --> 01:03:30.510
in America back in,
where it happened.

01:03:30.510 --> 01:03:33.420
And the surrounding communities.

01:03:33.420 --> 01:03:34.720
&gt;&gt; Randall Goldberg: It's hard.

01:03:34.720 --> 01:03:36.030
I haven't found, as
I wrote in the paper,

01:03:36.030 --> 01:03:39.520
I really haven't found
documented performances.

01:03:39.520 --> 01:03:42.200
Si it's hard, you know, it's
hard to find information

01:03:42.200 --> 01:03:43.500
